Using the movies DataFrame, create a visualization that shows the number of movies for each decade from the 1900s to the 2010s. Use the number in parentheses (e.g. (1975)) at the end of the title as the year. Drop all rows that do not have a valid year.

Hint: The year is always the middle 4 characters of the last 6 characters of the title. You can use the str accessor to extract the year from the title.

movies['year'] = movies['title'].str[-5:-1]

movies['year'] = pd.to_numeric(movies['year'], errors='coerce')
movies = movies.dropna(subset=['year'])

Q2:¶

Create a visualization that shows the number of movies in each genre.

Hint: the pd.DataFrame.explode() function might be useful here.

Be sure that your axis labels are legible!

In [ ]:
movies = movies.dropna(subset=['genres'])

movies = movies[movies['genres'].apply(lambda x: isinstance(x, str))]

movies['genres'] = movies['genres'].str.split('|')
movies_exploded = movies.explode('genres')

genre_counts = movies_exploded['genres'].value_counts().reset_index()
genre_counts.columns = ['genre', 'number_of_movies']

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.barplot(x='number_of_movies', y='genre', data=genre_counts)
plt.title('Number of Movies per Genre')
plt.xlabel('Number of Movies')
plt.ylabel('Genre')
plt.show()

Q3b:¶

What do you notice about the relative number of whole-number ratings (1,2,3,4,and 5) compared to the half-ratings (0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5)? Investigate the data further to see if you can figure out why that's the case. (Hint: a scatterplot showing the ratings vs. time might be helpful.)

We can see that when the ratings are whole numbers, there is a much higher volume of frequencies. When looking at the data more clearly, we can see that whenever there is a whole number rating, the line on the bar graph spikes indicating that there are far more ratings that are whole numbers, than ratings that are half numbers.

Q5:¶

Create a visualization showing the number of ratings produced on each day of the week.

Hint: the pd.to_datetime() function might be useful here, as well as the dt accessor.

Make sure your axis labels are in a reasonable order.

In [ ]:
ratings['timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(ratings['timestamp'], unit='s')
ratings['day_of_week'] = ratings['timestamp'].dt.day_name()

ratings_per_day = ratings['day_of_week'].value_counts(sort=False).reindex(['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday'])

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

sns.barplot(x=ratings_per_day.index, y=ratings_per_day.values)

plt.title('Number of Ratings on Each Day of the Week')
plt.xlabel('Day of the Week')
plt.ylabel('Number of Ratings')

plt.show()

Q7:¶

Create a visualization that shows the average rating for each genre.

In [ ]:
movies = pd.read_csv('~/Downloads/ml-latest-small/movies.csv')
ratings = pd.read_csv('~/Downloads/ml-latest-small/ratings.csv')


merged_df = pd.merge(movies, ratings, on='movieId')

merged_df['genres'] = merged_df['genres'].str.split('|')
exploded_df = merged_df.explode('genres')

average_ratings = exploded_df.groupby('genres')['rating'].mean().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.barplot(x='rating', y='genres', data=average_ratings.sort_values('rating', ascending=False), palette='viridis')

plt.title('Average Rating for Each Genre')
plt.xlabel('Average Rating')
plt.ylabel('Genre')
plt.show()

Q8:¶

Create a visualization that shows the distribution of the number of ratings of "good" movies (i.e., those with a mean rating of 3.5 or highter) and "bad" movies (i.e., those with a mean rating of less than 3.5), broken down by the decade when the movie was released.

Hint: You will need to join the movies and ratings DataFrames to get the decade information.

Hint: You may want to create a box plot or a violin plot (or both).

In [ ]:
movies = pd.read_csv('~/Downloads/ml-latest-small/movies.csv')
ratings = pd.read_csv('~/Downloads/ml-latest-small/ratings.csv')

movies['year'] = movies['title'].str.extract(r'\((\d{4})\)')
movies.dropna(subset=['year'], inplace=True) 
movies['year'] = movies['year'].astype(int)
movies['decade'] = (movies['year'] // 10 * 10).astype(str) + 's'

decade_order = ['1900s', '1910s', '1920s', '1930s', '1940s', '1950s', '1960s', '1970s', '1980s', '1990s', '2000s', '2010s']

merged_df = movies.merge(ratings, on='movieId')

merged_df = merged_df[merged_df['decade'].isin(decade_order)]

average_rating = merged_df.groupby('movieId')['rating'].mean().reset_index(name='average_rating')
average_rating['quality'] = average_rating['average_rating'].apply(lambda x: 'good' if x >= 3.5 else 'bad')

merged_df = merged_df.merge(average_rating, on='movieId')

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
sns.boxplot(x='decade', y='rating', hue='quality', data=merged_df, palette={'good': 'green', 'bad': 'red'}, order=decade_order)
plt.title('Distribution of Ratings of Good and Bad Movies by Decade')
plt.xlabel('Decade')
plt.ylabel('Ratings')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [ ]:
movies = pd.read_csv('~/Downloads/ml-latest-small/movies.csv')
ratings = pd.read_csv('~/Downloads/ml-latest-small/ratings.csv')

movies['year'] = movies['title'].str.extract(r'\((\d{4})\)')
movies.dropna(subset=['year'], inplace=True)
movies['year'] = movies['year'].astype(int)
movies['decade'] = (movies['year'] // 10 * 10).astype(str) + 's'

decade_order = ['1900s', '1910s', '1920s', '1930s', '1940s', '1950s', '1960s', '1970s', '1980s', '1990s', '2000s', '2010s']

merged_df = movies.merge(ratings, on='movieId')

merged_df = merged_df[merged_df['decade'].isin(decade_order)]

average_rating = merged_df.groupby('movieId')['rating'].mean().reset_index(name='average_rating')
average_rating['quality'] = average_rating['average_rating'].apply(lambda x: 'good' if x >= 3.5 else 'bad')

merged_df = merged_df.merge(average_rating, on='movieId')

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
sns.violinplot(x='decade', y='rating', hue='quality', data=merged_df, split=True, inner='quart', linewidth=1, palette={'good': 'lime', 'bad': 'red'}, order=decade_order)
plt.title('Distribution of Ratings of Good and Bad Movies by Decade')
plt.xlabel('Decade')
plt.ylabel('Ratings')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
